The short answer: you wrote chaptitre instead of chapitre 

For what are you using the  ` [\\divxlc]` part in the code? &lt;br&gt;
For example: `^chapitre [\\divxlc]`&lt;br&gt;
`^` means at the start of a row&lt;br&gt;
`chapitre` matches just the word chapitre(only lowercase)&lt;br&gt;
` `the blank field matches the space&lt;br&gt;
and the part `[\\divxlc]` matches only &#39;\&#39;, &#39;d&#39;, &#39;i&#39;,&#39;v&#39;,&#39;x&#39;,&#39;l&#39; or &#39;c&#39;

So it could match these examples:
**chapitre d**, **chapitre i**, or **chapitre \\**

And if you want the c at the start of chapitre to be uppercase or lowercase you could use this: &lt;br&gt;
`^[cC]hapitre [\\divxlc]`

