1. Make sure you wrapped your app hierarchy with the React-router `&lt;Switch&gt;` component and defined your routes properly, switch iterate over the possible available paths allow you to handle errors using the path variable.
2. It is better to write condition in render using the `&amp;&amp;` mark. eg: `return (this.state.ReturnToHome &amp;&amp; &lt;Redirect to=&quot;/&quot; /&gt;)` and this will do the job.

Theoretically, on every state update, the component should update and will update and will render eventually, so the problem isn&#39;t in the render function.

so here is some example for your case:

    export class App extends React.component {
    .....
    render() {
        return &lt;ReactRouter&gt;
                    &lt;Switch&gt;
                          &lt;Route exact path=&quot;/&quot; render={homeComponent} /&gt;
                          &lt;Route path=&quot;/create&quot; render={createComponent}/&gt;&lt;/Switch&gt; 
               &lt;/ReactRouter&gt;
    }
    export class CreateComponent extends React.component {
        constructor(){
             this.state = {
                  ReturnToHome: false
             }
